module lir
  source: ["lir.ly"]
  why: "Low-level Intermediate Representation. Defines LType, LValue, LExpr, LStmt, LProgram — the target of lowering from AST and the input to the C backend. Structured control flow (not basic blocks); flat expressions with SSA-like temps."

  doc "Architecture":
    """
    LIR sits between the AST and the C backend in the pipeline:

      AST + Checker annotations → Lowerer → LProgram
        → Optimizer → Monomorphizer → Memory Pass → C Backend

    Key properties:
    - All expressions are flattened to SSA-like temps (%0, %1, ...).
      Sub-expressions never nest; every operand is an LValue.
    - Structured control flow is preserved: StIf, StWhile, StFor,
      StSwitch — no basic-block graph.
    - Enums become tagged unions with integer tags and per-variant
      field data (LTyTaggedUnion + LVariant).
    - Classes become heap handles (LTyClassHandle), already a pointer.
    - try (?) is expanded to extract+check+early-return.
    - The memory pass rewrites ExClassAlloc → ExSlabAlloc and inserts
      RC instrumentation (StRefIncr/StRefDecr, StSliceRetain, frees).

    Memory model:
    - `permanent` classes (AST/LIR/CGen, ~34 compiler-internal classes)
      skip all RC: no _rc field, no inc/dec, freed by slab destruction.
    - `owned` classes are children in `owns` relations; their lifetime
      is managed by the parent's destructor, not by RC.
    - RC-eligible classes are non-permanent AND non-owned (currently
      StringBuilder, Dict and friends). They get an _rc field
      (AoS struct) or _rc parallel array (SoA slab).

    Post-lowering pass `resolve_class_types()` walks every LType in
    the program (struct/class fields, function params, return types,
    expression types) and populates class_decl / is_permanent /
    is_owned on each LType. The memory pass depends on this metadata
    to decide which types need RC instrumentation.

    LProgram flags drive the backend:
    - slab_mode / slab_mode_soa — AoS vs SoA slab allocation.
    - detect_uaf — sets _rc = UINT32_MAX on free and checks on every
      field access (use-after-free detection).
    - rc_free — actually call slab_free when _rc drops to 0 (opt-in).
    - owned_classes — Dict<Sym, bool> of classes that are relation
      children.
    """

  invariant "Nullable Variant Fields":
    procedural
    """
    LIR sum types (LExpr, LStmt, LValue, LType) use the same
    nullable-per-variant encoding as the AST: a discriminator `kind`
    plus one nullable field per variant carrying the variant's data.

    - LExpr has bin_op: LBinOpData?, call: LCallData?, etc. Exactly
      one of these is non-null per node, selected by `kind: LExprKind`.
    - LStmt has temp_def: LTempDef?, assign: LAssignData?, etc.,
      selected by `kind: LStmtKind`.
    - LValue carries variant-specific scalar fields (int_val, str_val,
      temp_id, name, ...) plus collection/index for ValIndexRef and
      ValClassFieldRef, selected by `kind: LValueKind`.

    Rationale: void* in C has no type recovery, so a single tagged
    payload pointer would force unsafe casts in the backend. Nullable
    per-variant fields preserve typing through codegen.
    """

  invariant "Expression Flattening":
    procedural
    """
    Every sub-expression is assigned to a unique temp BEFORE being
    used. Source `a + b * c` lowers to:
        %0 = b * c        // LTempDef { id: 0, expr: ExBinOp(b, *, c) }
        %1 = a + %0       // LTempDef { id: 1, expr: ExBinOp(a, +, %0) }

    Backends NEVER see nested LExpr — every operand inside an
    LExpr is an LValue (LValTemp, LValVar, ValGlobal, or a literal
    ValLit*). The temp counter is per-function and resets on each
    LFuncDecl.
    """

  invariant "While Loop Conditions":
    procedural
    """
    While-loop conditions are represented as `cond_block: [LStmt?]`
    plus `cond_var: LValue?`. Statements in cond_block compute the
    boolean condition into cond_var. The backend re-evaluates
    cond_block on every iteration without duplicating source — this
    keeps complex conditions (containing calls, temps, short-circuit
    chains) representable without violating expression flattening.
    """

  invariant "Type System":
    procedural
    """
    LTypeKind covers all backend-visible types:
      LTyInt-family (I8/I16/I32/I64, PlatformInt),
      LTyUint-family (U8/U16/U32/U64, PlatformUint),
      LTyFloat-family (F32/F64),
      LTyBool, LTyString, LTyUnit, LTyError,
      LTySlice, LTyMap, LTyTuple, LTyOptional, LTyChannel,
      LTyGenerator, LTyMutex,
      LTyStruct, LTyClassHandle, LTyTaggedUnion, LTyFuncPtr,
      LTyTypeVar, LTyAny, LTyErrorResult, LTyUnion.

    Semantics:
    - LTyAny is the fallback for unresolved types — emitted as void*
      in C. Its presence in the final program indicates the checker
      failed to annotate an expression.
    - LTyClassHandle means "pointer to a heap-allocated class" —
      it is itself a pointer; no extra indirection in C.
    - LTyErrorResult wraps (T, error) tuples with value/error fields,
      mirroring the checker's ErrorResult.
    - LTyTaggedUnion represents enum types as integer tag + per-variant
      field block. `variants: [LVariant]` carries the layout.

    LType also carries class metadata populated by
    resolve_class_types(): class_decl, is_permanent, is_owned. These
    are nil/false until that pass has run.
    """

  typedef LTypeKind: enum { TyI8, TyI16, TyI32, TyI64, TyU8, TyU16, TyU32, TyU64, TyF32, TyF64, TyBool, TyString, TyUnit, TyError, TyPlatformInt, TyPlatformUint, TyStruct, TyClassHandle, TyTuple, TySlice, TyMap, TyChannel, TyGenerator, TyMutex, TyOptional, TyTaggedUnion, TyFuncPtr, TyErrorResult, TyAny, TyTypeVar, TyUnion }
    source: lir.ly:7

